        <section xml:id="sec-quotient-spaces"><title>Quotient Spaces</title>
          
          <definition xml:id="def-quotient-topology">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space and let âˆ¼ be an equivalence relation on X. Let X/âˆ¼ be the set of equivalence classes and let q: X â†’ X/âˆ¼ be the equivalence map (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X). The quotient topology, or identification topology on X/âˆ¼ induced by âˆ¼, is the topology ğ’¯âˆ¼ = ğ’¯quo:= {U âŠ† X/âˆ¼ | q -1(U) is open in X}. The set X/âˆ¼ together with the quotient topology is called a quotient space of X, and the equivalence map q is called the quotient map induced by âˆ¼.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-quotient-topology">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The quotient topology is a topology.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-293">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If X/âˆ¼ is a quotient space of X and q: X â†’ X/âˆ¼ is the equivalence map (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X), then q is a continuous surjection. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The quotient topology induced by an equivalence relation is the largest topology on the set of equivalence classes for which the equivalence map is continuous.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-induced-quotient-topology">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let (X,ğ’¯X) be a topological space, let Y be a set, and let f:X â†’ Y be a surjective function. The quotient topology on Y induced by f is ğ’¯q := {V âŠ† Y | f-1(V) âˆˆ ğ’¯X}. If Y has the quotient topology induced by f then f is called a quotient map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-induced-quotient-topology">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The quotient topology induced by a function f is a topology.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-298">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f is a quotient map, then f is a continuous surjection.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The quotient topology induced by a map f is the largest topology on the codomain of f for which the map f is continuous.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2100">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X be a topological space. 
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If âˆ¼ is an equivalence relation on X, then the quotient topology on X/âˆ¼ induced by âˆ¼ equals the quotient topology on X/âˆ¼ induced by the equivalence map q:X â†’ X/âˆ¼ (defined by q(p) := [p] for all p in X). 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f:X â†’ Y is a surjection, then the quotient space (Y,ğ’¯f) is homeomorphic to the quotient space (X/âˆ¼,ğ’¯âˆ¼) induced by the equivalence relation on X defined by x âˆ¼ x' if and only if f(x) = f(x') for all x,x' âˆˆ X; moreover, the homeomorphism g:X/âˆ¼ â†’ Y satisfies g âˆ˜ q = f, where q is the equivalence map.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2104">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = [0,1] have the Euclidean subspace topology, and let âˆ¼ be the equivalence relation on X defined by p âˆ¼ q if and only if either [p=q] or [{p,q} = {0,1}]. Then the quotient space X/âˆ¼ is isomorphic to S1.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <example>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The torus T2 is the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (r,1) and (0,s) âˆ¼ (1,s) for all r,s âˆˆ [0,1]. 
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The Klein bottle K2 is the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (r,1) and (0,s) âˆ¼ (1,1-s) for all r,s âˆˆ [0,1].
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The Mobius band M2 is the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (1-r,1) for all r âˆˆ [0,1].
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    The projective plane P2 is the quotient space P2 := S2/âˆ¼ where S2 := {(x,y,z) âˆˆ â„3 | x2 + y2 + z2 = 1} is the 2-sphere (with the Euclidean subspace topology) and âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation generated by (x,y,z) âˆ¼ (-x,-y,-z) for all (x,y,z) âˆˆ S2.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </example>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-2110">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X = [0,1] Ã— [0,1] have the product topology (where each [0,1] has the Euclidean subspace topology).
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The cylinder S1 Ã— [0,1] is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (1,r) for all r âˆˆ [0,1]. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The projective plane P2 is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (1-r,1) and (0,1-s) âˆ¼ (1,s) for all r,s âˆˆ [0,1]. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The 2-sphere S2 is homeomorphic to the quotient space X/âˆ¼ where âˆ¼ is the equivalence relation on X generated by (r,0) âˆ¼ (0,r) and (s,1) âˆ¼ (1,s) for all r,s âˆˆ [0,1]. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The torus T2 is homeomorphic to the product space S1 Ã— S1 where each S1 has the Euclidean subspace topology.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-cfbt">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X and Z be topological spaces, let âˆ¼ be an equivalence relation on X, let q: X â†’ X/âˆ¼ be the equivalence map, and let X/âˆ¼ have the quotient topology. Suppose that f: X â†’ Z is a continuous function that is constant on equivalence classes. Then:
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The map f induces a continuous function g: X/âˆ¼ â†’ Z with g âˆ˜ q = f. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f is onto then g is onto. If f is a quotient map, then g is a quotient map.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If [ f(x)=f(x') implies q(x)=q(x') for all x,x' âˆˆ X] then g is one-to-one.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If f is a quotient map and (3) holds then g is a homeomorphism.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <definition xml:id="def-open-map">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Let X and Y be topological spaces. An open map from X to Y is a function f:X â†’ Y such that for every open set V in X, the image f(V) is open in Y.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-open-map-properties">
            <statement>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      A composition of open functions is open. 
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If XÎ± has the topology TÎ± for each Î± âˆˆ J, and âˆÎ± âˆˆ J XÎ± has the product topology, then the projection map pÎ² : (âˆÎ± âˆˆ J XÎ±) â†’ XÎ² is open. 
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-cq2">
            <statement>
              <p>
                If f: X â†’ Z is continuous, onto, and open, then f is a quotient map.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>

          <proposition xml:id="prop-2127">
            <statement>
              <p>
                There exist quotient maps that are not open maps.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>

          <definition xml:id="def-topological-retraction">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A retraction of a topological space X to a subspace A is a continuous function r:X â†’ A satisfying r(a) = a for all a âˆˆ A.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>

          <theorem xml:id="thm-cq3">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Every retraction is a quotient map.
